window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>1>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"TRIAL BALANCE : ERRORS NOT DISCLOSED BY TRIAL BALANCE","question":"State three reasons why a trial balance may not balance.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Transposition of figures  - Partial recording of entries  - Single entry of a transaction  - Undercasting of transactions   - Overcasting of transaction  - Undercasting of balance  - Overcasting of balance  - Sliding error.","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>1>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"TRIAL BALANCE : ERRORS NOT DISCLOSED BY TRIAL BALANCE","question":"State three errors that would not affect the agreement of the trial balance.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Error of principle  - Error of omission  - Error of commission  - Compensating error  - Error of complete reversal of entry  - Duplicating error  - Error of original entry.","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>1>c","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SUSPENSE ACCOUNT : MEANING AND USES OF SUSPENSE ACCOUNT","question":"What is a suspense account?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Suspense account is a temporary account that accommodate the difference in trial balance pending the time the errors are located and corrected.","marks":"5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>2>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"DEPRECIATION OF FIXED ASSETS : MEANING AND REASONS FOR CHARGING DEPRECIATION","question":"What is depreciation?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Depreciation is defined as reduction in economic value of a fixed assets as a result of wear and tear, usage, passage of time, obsolescence and technological advancement.","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>2>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"DEPRECIATION OF FIXED ASSETS : CAUSES AND ELEMENTS OF DEPRECIATION","question":"Explain three factors that are taken into consideration in determining annual depreciation charge.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Original cost: This is the cost incurred in acquiring or purchasing or installing the asset.  Scrap value: This is also known as residual value. This is the amount realised from the sales of an asset at the end of it useful life.  Estimated useful life: This is the number of years the asset is expected to last or use.  Method of depreciation: This is the method that is to be used consistently in depreciating the asset through its life span.","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>2>c","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"DEPRECIATION OF FIXED ASSETS : MEANING AND REASONS FOR CHARGING DEPRECIATION","question":"State two reasons for charging depreciation.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- To help the firm spread the cost of the asset over its useful life.  - It helps in the determination of profit.  - It helps to determine the realistic value of an asset at its disposal.  - It helps to determine a fair value of assets in the balance sheet","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>3>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MANUFACTURING ACCOUNTS : INTRODUCTION AND PURPOSE","question":"Explain four classifications of cost found in the preparation of manufacturing accounts.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Direct Material Cost: This is the aggregate of the cost of basic raw materials input that are required for production.  - Direct Labour Cost: These are cost(wage) paid directly in the process of converting raw materials into finished goods (outputs).  - Overhead cost: These are cost paid indirectly in the process of converting raw materials into finished goods (outputs).  - Direct expenses: This is the amount of expenditure that are incurred for the purpose of production activities and which are directly incurred with the volume or quantity of output desired.","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>3>b>i","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MANUFACTURING ACCOUNTS : INTRODUCTION AND PURPOSE","question":"Explain the prime cost.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Prime cost: This is the total of all elements of cost such as direct labour, direct materials and direct expenses incurred in the production process.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>3>b>ii","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MANUFACTURING ACCOUNTS : INTRODUCTION AND PURPOSE","question":"Explain the work-in-progress.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Work-in-progress: These are partly produced or partly manufactured goods and at any stages between raw materials and finished goods.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>3>b>iii","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MANUFACTURING ACCOUNTS : INTRODUCTION AND PURPOSE","question":"Explain the manufacturing profit.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Manufacturing Profit: This is the profit deemed to have been made through manufacturing activities as distinct from buying the product for resale at the open market. It is the difference between factory cost of production and market value of the quantity produced.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>4>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ACCOUNTING : ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS AND CONVENTIONS","question":"Explain this concept and convention    money measurement.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Money Measurement: This is an accounting concept that assume that accounting records will be concerned with only those events which can be measured or expressed in terms of money or monetary terms.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>4>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ACCOUNTING : ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS AND CONVENTIONS","question":"Explain this concept and convention  business entity.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Business entity: This is an accounting concepts that assume that the affairs of a business will be treated as being quite separate from the non-business of its owner. It states that there is  distinct relationship between the business and its owner.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>4>c","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ACCOUNTING : ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS AND CONVENTIONS","question":"Explain this concept and convention  going-concern.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Going concern: This is an accounting concept that assume that establishment will continue to operate or exist into the unforseen future.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>4>d","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ACCOUNTING : ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS AND CONVENTIONS","question":"Explain this concept and convention  realisation.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Realisation: This is an accounting concept that assume that profit shall be taken to have been earned only when the transaction leading to it has been duly concluded or ascertained.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>4>e","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"e","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ACCOUNTING : ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS AND CONVENTIONS","question":"Explain this concept and convention  materiality.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Materiality: This is an accounting convention that emphasis significance, verifiability and sizeability of income and expenses.  It states that only those items in the accounts that are significant and likely to affect the view given by the financial statements should be disclosed.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>5>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"DEPRECIATION OF FIXED ASSETS : METHODS OF DEPRECIATION","question":"A manufacturing company prepares its account to 31st December each year. The company provides for depreciation on its plants at the rate of 10% per annum using the straight line method.  On 31st December 2001, the plant account consisted of three plants purchased as follows:  Date of Purchase  Plant X  Plant Y  Plant Z  1st July, 1999  1st January, 2000  1st October, 2001Cost (\u20a6)  60,000  80,000  30,000  The plant bought in July, 1999 was sold on 30th September, 2001 for \u20a655,000.  You are required prepare:    Plant Account.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>5>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"DEPRECIATION OF FIXED ASSETS : METHODS OF DEPRECIATION","question":"A manufacturing company prepares its account to 31st December each year. The company provides for depreciation on its plants at the rate of 10% per annum using the straight line method.  On 31st December 2001, the plant account consisted of three plants purchased as follows:  Date of Purchase  Plant X  Plant Y  Plant Z  1st July, 1999  1st January, 2000  1st October, 2001Cost (\u20a6)  60,000  80,000  30,000  The plant bought in July, 1999 was sold on 30th September, 2001 for \u20a655,000.  You are required prepare:  Provision for Depreciation Account.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>5>c","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"DEPRECIATION OF FIXED ASSETS : METHODS OF DEPRECIATION","question":"A manufacturing company prepares its account to 31st December each year. The company provides for depreciation on its plants at the rate of 10% per annum using the straight line method.  On 31st December 2001, the plant account consisted of three plants purchased as follows:  Date of Purchase  Plant X  Plant Y  Plant Z  1st July, 1999  1st January, 2000  1st October, 2001Cost (\u20a6)  60,000  80,000  30,000  The plant bought in July, 1999 was sold on 30th September, 2001 for \u20a655,000.  You are required prepare:  Plant Disposal Account.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Plant disposal account  30/9/01 Plant x  21/12/011 profit on sales60,000  8,50030/9/01 Prov. for dep.  30/9/01 Cash13,500  55,000 68,50068,500","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>6>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"CONTROL ACCOUNTS : SALES LEDGER CONTROL ACCOUNT","question":"The following balances were extracted from the books of Olusesi Enterprises on 31st March, 2003:    Sales ledger balance - 1/4/2002  Purchases ledger balance - 1/4/2002  Sales day book  Purchases day book  Cash received from customers  Cash paid to creditors  Returns outwards day book  Returns inwards day book  Bad debt written off  Bills dishonoured  Discounts allowed  Discount received  Credit notes received  Bills payable  Cash refund to customers   Debit notes issued  Bills receivable  Contra settlement  Cash refund from creditors\u20a6  22,000  30,000  420,000  331,000  119,000  132,000  5,000  4,000  600  4,500  1,200  700  800  200  500  1,340  800  300  1,000  You are required to prepare:    Sales Ledger Control Account","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>6>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"CONTROL ACCOUNTS : PURCHASES LEDGER CONTROL ACCOUNT","question":"The following balances were extracted from the books of Olusesi Enterprises on 31st March, 2003:    Sales ledger balance - 1/4/2002  Purchases ledger balance - 1/4/2002  Sales day book  Purchases day book  Cash received from customers  Cash paid to creditors  Returns outwards day book  Returns inwards day book  Bad debt written off  Bills dishonoured  Discounts allowed  Discount received  Credit notes received  Bills payable  Cash refund to customers   Debit notes issued  Bills receivable  Contra settlement  Cash refund from creditors\u20a6  22,000  30,000  420,000  331,000  119,000  132,000  5,000  4,000  600  4,500  1,200  700  800  200  500  1,340  800  300  1,000  You are required to prepare:  Purchases Ledger Control Account.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>7>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"DISSOLUTION OF PARTNERSHIP ACCOUNT : INTRODUCTION AND RULES FOR DISTRIBUTING OF ASSSETS","question":"Taiwo and Kehinde had been in partnership for several years sharing profits and losses in the ratio of capitals. On 31st December, 2003, they decided to dissolve their partnership on which date their Balace Sheet was as follows:  TAIWO AND KEHINDE  Balance Sheet as at 31st December, 2003    Capital:  Taiwo  Kehinde\u20a6    60,000  40,000  Fixtures and Fittings  Stock  Debtors  Cash\u20a6  40,000  58,000  45,000  7,000Current:  Taiwo  Kehinde  Trade creditors  Bank overdraft  8,000  (3,000)  15,000  30,000110,000      15,00015,000    Additional information  (a) Fixtures and Fittings were sold for \u20a636,000  (b) Taiwo took over part of the stock at an agreed value of \u20a625,000 while the rest sold for \u20a632,000.  (c) Debtors realised \u20a643,600   (d) Trade creditors were settled for \u20a612,800  (e) Cash and proceeds from realisation were banked to liquidate the overdraft  (f) Dissolution expenses amounted to \u20a61,800  You are required to prepare    Realisation Account.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>7>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"DISSOLUTION OF PARTNERSHIP ACCOUNT : INTRODUCTION AND RULES FOR DISTRIBUTING OF ASSSETS","question":"Taiwo and Kehinde had been in partnership for several years sharing profits and losses in the ratio of capitals. On 31st December, 2003, they decided to dissolve their partnership on which date their Balace Sheet was as follows:  TAIWO AND KEHINDE  Balance Sheet as at 31st December, 2003    Capital:  Taiwo  Kehinde\u20a6    60,000  40,000  Fixtures and Fittings  Stock  Debtors  Cash\u20a6  40,000  58,000  45,000  7,000Current:  Taiwo  Kehinde  Trade creditors  Bank overdraft  8,000  (3,000)  15,000  30,000110,000      15,00015,000    Additional information  (a) Fixtures and Fittings were sold for \u20a636,000  (b) Taiwo took over part of the stock at an agreed value of \u20a625,000 while the rest sold for \u20a632,000.  (c) Debtors realised \u20a643,600   (d) Trade creditors were settled for \u20a612,800  (e) Cash and proceeds from realisation were banked to liquidate the overdraft  (f) Dissolution expenses amounted to \u20a61,800  You are required to prepare  Bank Account.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>7>c","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"DISSOLUTION OF PARTNERSHIP ACCOUNT : INTRODUCTION AND RULES FOR DISTRIBUTING OF ASSSETS","question":"Taiwo and Kehinde had been in partnership for several years sharing profits and losses in the ratio of capitals. On 31st December, 2003, they decided to dissolve their partnership on which date their Balace Sheet was as follows:  TAIWO AND KEHINDE  Balance Sheet as at 31st December, 2003    Capital:  Taiwo  Kehinde\u20a6    60,000  40,000  Fixtures and Fittings  Stock  Debtors  Cash\u20a6  40,000  58,000  45,000  7,000Current:  Taiwo  Kehinde  Trade creditors  Bank overdraft  8,000  (3,000)  15,000  30,000110,000      15,00015,000    Additional information  (a) Fixtures and Fittings were sold for \u20a636,000  (b) Taiwo took over part of the stock at an agreed value of \u20a625,000 while the rest sold for \u20a632,000.  (c) Debtors realised \u20a643,600   (d) Trade creditors were settled for \u20a612,800  (e) Cash and proceeds from realisation were banked to liquidate the overdraft  (f) Dissolution expenses amounted to \u20a61,800  You are required to prepare  Partner's Capital and Current Accounts.","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>8>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"COMPANY ACCOUNT : FINAL ACCOUNTS OF A LIMITED COMPANY AND TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The following Trial Balance was extracted from the books of Linguere Limited on 31st December, 2003 after the Trading Account had been prepared.  LINGUERE LIMITED  Trial Balance as at 31st December, 2003.  ParticularsDebitCredit  Ordinary Share Capital:  500,000 Ordinary Shares of D1 each  Share Premium  Profit and Loss  Freehold Premises (at cost)  Stock (31/12/2003)  Gross Profit  Discounts  Wages and Salaries  General Office expenses  Motor vehicles (at cost)  Prov. for depreciation (motor vehicles)  Interim dividends  Debtors and creditors  Cash and BankD    500,000      250,000  16,300  110,790  350  12,400  14,050  200,000    40,000  22,400  128,800D      20,000  15,000    260        20,000      18,250  684,300684,300    Additional information  (a) Wages and salaries accrued was D600  (b) Provide for depreciation on motor vehicles at 10% on reducing balance basis.  (c) Transfer D15,000 to general reserve.  (d) Final dividends proposed is 5Butus per share.  You are required to prepare    Profit and Loss Account for the year ended 31st December, 2003.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>8>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"COMPANY ACCOUNT : FINAL ACCOUNTS OF A LIMITED COMPANY AND TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The following Trial Balance was extracted from the books of Linguere Limited on 31st December, 2003 after the Trading Account had been prepared.  LINGUERE LIMITED  Trial Balance as at 31st December, 2003.  ParticularsDebitCredit  Ordinary Share Capital:  500,000 Ordinary Shares of D1 each  Share Premium  Profit and Loss  Freehold Premises (at cost)  Stock (31/12/2003)  Gross Profit  Discounts  Wages and Salaries  General Office expenses  Motor vehicles (at cost)  Prov. for depreciation (motor vehicles)  Interim dividends  Debtors and creditors  Cash and BankD    500,000      250,000  16,300  110,790  350  12,400  14,050  200,000    40,000  22,400  128,800D      20,000  15,000    260        20,000      18,250  684,300684,300    Additional information  (a) Wages and salaries accrued was D600  (b) Provide for depreciation on motor vehicles at 10% on reducing balance basis.  (c) Transfer D15,000 to general reserve.  (d) Final dividends proposed is 5Butus per share.  You are required to prepare  Profit and Loss Appropriation Account for the year ended 31st December, 2003","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>8>c","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"COMPANY ACCOUNT : FINAL ACCOUNTS OF A LIMITED COMPANY AND TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The following Trial Balance was extracted from the books of Linguere Limited on 31st December, 2003 after the Trading Account had been prepared.  LINGUERE LIMITED  Trial Balance as at 31st December, 2003.  ParticularsDebitCredit  Ordinary Share Capital:  500,000 Ordinary Shares of D1 each  Share Premium  Profit and Loss  Freehold Premises (at cost)  Stock (31/12/2003)  Gross Profit  Discounts  Wages and Salaries  General Office expenses  Motor vehicles (at cost)  Prov. for depreciation (motor vehicles)  Interim dividends  Debtors and creditors  Cash and BankD    500,000      250,000  16,300  110,790  350  12,400  14,050  200,000    40,000  22,400  128,800D      20,000  15,000    260        20,000      18,250  684,300684,300    Additional information  (a) Wages and salaries accrued was D600  (b) Provide for depreciation on motor vehicles at 10% on reducing balance basis.  (c) Transfer D15,000 to general reserve.  (d) Final dividends proposed is 5Butus per share.  You are required to prepare  A Balance Sheet as at that date.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>9>a","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"THE LEDGER : APPLICATION OF DOUBLE ENTRY IN LEDGER","question":"The following Trial Balance was extracted from the books of Linguere Limited on 31st December, 2003 after the Trading Account had been prepared.  LINGUERE LIMITED  Trial Balance as at 31st December, 2003.  ParticularsDebitCredit  Ordinary Share Capital:  500,000 Ordinary Shares of D1 each  Share Premium  Profit and Loss  Freehold Premises (at cost)  Stock (31/12/2003)  Gross Profit  Discounts  Wages and Salaries  General Office expenses  Motor vehicles (at cost)  Prov. for depreciation (motor vehicles)  Interim dividends  Debtors and creditors  Cash and BankD    500,000      250,000  16,300  110,790  350  12,400  14,050  200,000    40,000  22,400  128,800D      20,000  15,000    260        20,000      18,250  684,300684,300    Additional information  (a) Wages and salaries accrued was D600  (b) Provide for depreciation on motor vehicles at 10% on reducing balance basis.  (c) Transfer D15,000 to general reserve.  (d) Final dividends proposed is 5Butus per share.  You are required to prepare  Amy Wadada started business as a retailer on 1st January, 2003 with an initial capital of \u20a6500,000.  The following is a summary of her business transactions during the first six months of trading:  (a) A delivery van was bought on 15th January, 2003 at a cost of \u20a6240,000 for cash.  (b) Cash sales totalled \u20a6600,000  (c) Rent of \u20a6180,000 was paid on the commencement of the business.  (d) During the period Wadada withdrew goods worth \u20a660,000 and cash of \u20a670,000 from the business for personal use.  (e) Credit sales amounted to \u20a6400,000 and \u20a6120,000 out of this amount was outstanding as at 30th June, 2003.  (f) An amount of \u20a685,000 was paid for general expenses.  (g) During the period suppliers were paid \u20a6450,000 for goods and invoices totalling \u20a680,000 remained unpaid at 30th June, 2003.  You are required to:  Write up the Ledger Accounts.","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Dr &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Capital Account &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Cr    bal c/d\u20a6  500,000  Jan 1 &nbsp &nbsp Cash\u20a6  500,000bal b/d500,000","marks":"15","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Accounts>2005>9>b","subject":"Accounts","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"COMPANY ACCOUNT : FINAL ACCOUNTS OF A LIMITED COMPANY AND TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The following Trial Balance was extracted from the books of Linguere Limited on 31st December, 2003 after the Trading Account had been prepared.  LINGUERE LIMITED  Trial Balance as at 31st December, 2003.  ParticularsDebitCredit  Ordinary Share Capital:  500,000 Ordinary Shares of D1 each  Share Premium  Profit and Loss  Freehold Premises (at cost)  Stock (31/12/2003)  Gross Profit  Discounts  Wages and Salaries  General Office expenses  Motor vehicles (at cost)  Prov. for depreciation (motor vehicles)  Interim dividends  Debtors and creditors  Cash and BankD    500,000      250,000  16,300  110,790  350  12,400  14,050  200,000    40,000  22,400  128,800D      20,000  15,000    260        20,000      18,250  684,300684,300    Additional information  (a) Wages and salaries accrued was D600  (b) Provide for depreciation on motor vehicles at 10% on reducing balance basis.  (c) Transfer D15,000 to general reserve.  (d) Final dividends proposed is 5Butus per share.  You are required to prepare  Extract a Trial Balance as at 30th June, 2003.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"}];